# Decision Model

**QORWAY Decision Intelligence Infrastructure**

> In QORWAY, a decision is not a text output.  
> A decision is a structured, traceable, constrained, and executable system object.

---

## 1. Purpose

This document defines the public-facing decision model used by QORWAY.

The Decision Model explains how QORWAY treats decisions as governed system objects that move through the full infrastructure:

```text
data → graph → Atlas → Domain Packs → PolicyCore → PulseFlow → GreenCore → execution → feedback
````

This document is intentionally high-level.

Implementation schemas, internal contracts, scoring logic, and execution rules are proprietary and maintained in private repositories.

---

## 2. Definition

A QORWAY decision is a structured system object representing a proposed course of action generated through causal reasoning and domain context.

A decision must be:

* causal
* contextual
* constrained
* executable
* auditable
* tenant-scoped
* feedback-linked

A decision is invalid if it cannot be traced.

---

## 3. Role in QORWAY OS

The decision is the central object of the QORWAY runtime.

It connects:

| Layer            | Relationship to Decision                        |
| ---------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| Knowledge Graph  | Stores signals, causal structures, and evidence |
| Atlas            | Generates the causal decision                   |
| Domain Packs     | Provide domain context and decision policies    |
| PolicyCore       | Validates constraints                           |
| PulseFlow        | Converts the decision into execution events     |
| GreenCore        | Optimizes the execution route                   |
| Agents / Systems | Execute the approved path                       |
| Feedback Loop    | Measures the result and updates learning        |

The decision object is the bridge between reasoning and execution.

---

## 4. Decision Lifecycle

A QORWAY decision follows a governed lifecycle:

```text
CREATED
  ↓
REASONED
  ↓
CONTEXTUALIZED
  ↓
VALIDATED
  ↓
APPROVED / MODIFIED / REJECTED
  ↓
ORCHESTRATED
  ↓
OPTIMIZED
  ↓
EXECUTED
  ↓
OBSERVED
  ↓
LEARNED
```

Each lifecycle stage must be traceable.

---

## 5. Conceptual Decision Structure

A QORWAY decision can be understood as a structured object composed of several conceptual sections.

```text
Decision
├── Identity
├── Tenant Boundary
├── Source Context
├── Domain Context
├── Causal Lineage
├── Recommended Action
├── Constraint Validation
├── Execution Reference
├── Optimization Reference
├── Feedback Reference
└── Audit Metadata
```

This structure is conceptual.

The internal data model is proprietary.

---

## 6. Identity

Each decision must have a unique identity.

Identity allows the system to track a decision across:

* reasoning
* validation
* execution
* optimization
* feedback
* audit

A decision without identity cannot be governed.

---

## 7. Tenant Boundary

Every decision must belong to a tenant boundary.

Tenant scope ensures:

* data isolation
* graph isolation
* execution isolation
* feedback isolation
* audit isolation

Core rule:

> A decision without tenant scope is invalid.

---

## 8. Source Context

A decision must be linked to the signal or situation that triggered it.

Source context may include:

* enterprise data signal
* Knowledge Graph update
* operational event
* human input
* regulatory change
* feedback signal
* risk activation

This ensures the system can explain why the decision exists.

---

## 9. Domain Context

A decision must be linked to its Domain Pack where domain logic is required.

Domain context may include:

* Domain Pack name
* Domain Pack version
* relevant domain rules
* available actions
* gates
* risks
* outcomes

Domain context ensures that decisions are not generic.

Core rule:

> Atlas reasons. Domain Packs contextualize.

---

## 10. Causal Lineage

Every QORWAY decision must include causal lineage.

Causal lineage explains:

* what signal changed
* what causal chain was activated
* what risk or opportunity emerged
* why the recommended action exists
* what outcome is expected

A decision without causal lineage is not a QORWAY decision.

---

## 11. Recommended Action

A decision may produce one or more recommended actions.

A recommended action must be:

* linked to causal reasoning
* compatible with the Domain Pack
* eligible for PolicyCore validation
* executable through PulseFlow where required
* measurable through feedback

Recommended actions are not free-form suggestions.

They are structured execution candidates.

---

## 12. Constraint Validation

Before execution, a decision must pass PolicyCore validation.

PolicyCore may return:

```text
APPROVED
MODIFIED
REJECTED
```

Only approved or modified-and-approved decisions can move toward execution.

Core rule:

> No PolicyCore validation → no execution.

---

## 13. Execution Reference

Executable decisions must be linked to PulseFlow.

PulseFlow converts validated decisions into:

* execution events
* workflows
* agent tasks
* system actions
* execution logs
* feedback signals

Core rule:

> Atlas cannot execute directly. PulseFlow executes validated decisions.

---

## 14. Optimization Reference

Approved execution paths may be optimized by GreenCore.

GreenCore evaluates:

* local execution
* edge execution
* cloud execution
* compute cost
* latency
* carbon footprint
* sovereignty constraints
* tenant execution policy

Core rule:

> GreenCore optimizes approved paths. It cannot override PolicyCore.

---

## 15. Feedback Reference

Every measurable decision should define how the system will observe the result.

Feedback may include:

* actual outcome
* expected vs actual deviation
* execution delay
* financial impact
* operational impact
* compliance impact
* carbon / compute impact
* human approval outcome

Feedback enables QORWAY to learn from execution reality.

---

## 16. Audit Metadata

Every decision must be audit-ready.

Audit metadata should allow the system to reconstruct:

```text
What decision was made?
Why was it made?
Which domain context applied?
Which constraints were checked?
How was it executed?
Where was it executed?
What happened afterward?
What did the system learn?
```

A decision is invalid if the audit trail cannot be reconstructed.

---

## 17. Human Approval

Some decisions may require human approval.

Human approval may be required by:

* PolicyCore
* tenant policy
* Domain Pack rules
* regulatory classification
* financial exposure
* ESG impact
* public interest
* low confidence
* simulation drift

Human approval must be logged and linked to the decision trace.

---

## 18. Decision Quality Signals

QORWAY may attach quality signals to decisions.

Examples include:

* clarity
* complexity
* expected impact
* confidence
* reversibility
* risk exposure
* constraint burden
* execution feasibility

These signals help determine:

* priority
* review depth
* human oversight needs
* execution urgency
* monitoring intensity

The detailed scoring model is proprietary.

---

## 19. Decision Integrity Rules

A QORWAY decision is invalid if:

* it has no tenant boundary
* it has no causal lineage
* it lacks required domain context
* it bypasses PolicyCore
* it executes outside PulseFlow
* it has no audit metadata
* it has no execution path where execution is required
* it has no feedback pathway where outcome is measurable
* it cannot be reconstructed from evidence

---

## 20. Public vs Private Boundary

This public document defines the conceptual interface of the QORWAY Decision Model.

It does not expose:

* internal schemas
* production JSON contracts
* scoring algorithms
* PolicyCore rule implementation
* PulseFlow event contracts
* GreenCore routing logic
* Domain Pack internals
* prompts
* proprietary causal models

Those components belong in private repositories.

---

## 21. What the Decision Model Is Not

The Decision Model is not:

* a prompt format
* a chatbot answer
* a report template
* a task list
* a dashboard card
* a workflow alone
* a public implementation contract

It is the conceptual system object that links reasoning, governance, execution, and learning.

---

## 22. Strategic Importance

The Decision Model is central to QORWAY’s architecture.

It ensures that every decision is:

* structured
* explainable
* governed
* executable
* measurable
* auditable
* reusable for learning

Without a structured decision model, QORWAY would produce recommendations.

With it, QORWAY produces decision infrastructure.

---

## 23. Final Statement

A QORWAY decision is a causal, contextual, constrained, executable, and auditable system object.

Final system statement:

> The Decision Model is where QORWAY turns reasoning into governable action.

